<p>Reviewed in:<br>
Fanfare (Vol./#-p.): 22/4- (Marc/Apr 1999)
</p>

<p>Ludus Danielis (the &quot;Play of Daniel&quot;) is the richest
of the medieval liturgical dramas for its sophistication and variety.
The manuscript dates from c.1230, although the work is thought to
have been performed in the later 12th century at Beauvais Cathedral.</p>

<p>The music is entirely monophonic as written, although there are
various choruses and remarks on instrumental accompaniment.  The
present performance not only improvises various drone-style
accompaniments, but even some &quot;real&quot; polyphony in the
conductus settings.

<p>Names given parenthentically for performers are voice roles.</p>

